        "content": "<p>I'm still not sure if what I call a Prüfer ring must be called a Prüfer ring. I was just reading two minutes ago that there are several nonequivalent extensions of the notion of Prüfer domain to rings with zero divisors.  But you made a lot of work for me by giving a  sketch of why Prüfer domains verify the intersection property. That's some good progress :)</p>",
        "id": 421147188,
        "sender_full_name": "Jean-Baptiste Vienney",
        "timestamp": 1707779440
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, I'm not at all versed in all this. But that theorem I pointed to seems to contain answers to the other questions you ask, to the effect that a ring is coherent iff the intersection of any two finitely generated ideals is again finitely generated.</p>",
